{"id":743,"date":"2021-04-11T23:22:08","date_gmt":"2021-04-11T23:22:08","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/programming.sdarobotics.org\/?page_id=743"},"modified":"2024-09-02T19:29:09","modified_gmt":"2024-09-02T19:29:09","slug":"testing-the-wiring","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/testing-the-wiring\/","title":{"rendered":"Testing the wiring"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>To test the wiring, we are going to use the program <strong>WiringTests <\/strong>which can be found in the <strong>VSCode <\/strong>folder of the <strong>RobotTools2021 <\/strong>that you can find here. If you don&#8217;t yet know how to load and run programs using Visual Studio Code, please review the following chapter of the <strong>Minibot<\/strong> tutorial: <strong><a href=\"\/running-the-program\/\" data-type=\"page\">Running the program<\/a><\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To test the wiring, load the <strong>WiringTests <\/strong>program into Visual Studio Code by choosing the <strong>File \/ Open Folder<\/strong> command and selecting the <strong>WiringTests <\/strong>folder found in <strong>VSCode<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Then execute the program and start the <strong>Pi Driver Station<\/strong> and enable the virtual joystick and <strong>Connect <\/strong>and <strong>Enable <\/strong>the robot.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Test 1 &#8211; Test the left motor and left encoder<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Press and hold the <strong>B1<\/strong> button. The left motor should turn on and the robot should turn right. If the motor runs backwards, or the right motor runs instead, check you motor connections.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>After you release the button, the robot should stop. Then check the Terminal window at the bottom of the screen in <strong>VS Code<\/strong>. You should see something like:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"485\" height=\"224\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftMotorTest.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-747\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftMotorTest.jpg 485w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/LeftMotorTest-300x139.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 485px) 100vw, 485px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This should show the speed of the robot. If the speed is zero or negative then you need to check the encoder connections.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Test 2 &#8211; Test the right motor and right encoder<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Press and hold the <strong>B2<\/strong> button. The right motor should turn on and the robot should turn left. If the motor runs backwards, or the left motor runs instead, check you motor connections.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>As before, after you release the button, the robot should stop. Then check the Terminal window at the bottom of the screen in <strong>VS Code<\/strong>. You should see something like:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"453\" height=\"224\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightMotorTest.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-748\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightMotorTest.jpg 453w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/RightMotorTest-300x148.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 453px) 100vw, 453px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This should show the speed of the robot. If the speed is zero or negative then you need to check the encoder connections.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Once the motors are working correctly, you should be able to drive the robot with the virtual joystick.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Test 3 &#8211; Test the left IR Sensor<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Before we run our test of the <strong>IR Sensors<\/strong>, we need to calibrate them. Take a white sheet and add a strip of black tape. Then turn the robot on and position it so that the two <strong>IR Sensors<\/strong> are over the white portion of the sheet. Then adjust the two little potentiometers so that the <strong>green <\/strong>light on the sensor comes on when the robot is over the white portion and turns off when it is over the black portion:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><a href=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-1024x354.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-749\" width=\"602\" height=\"208\" srcset=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-1024x354.jpg 1024w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-300x104.jpg 300w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-768x266.jpg 768w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-1536x531.jpg 1536w, http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/04\/IRWhiteBlack-2048x709.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 602px) 100vw, 602px\" \/><\/a><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now run the program and position the robot a few inches in front of the black tape. Then press button&nbsp;<strong>B3<\/strong>&nbsp;and the robot should drive forward until the <strong>left IR Sensor<\/strong> is over the black tap<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"font-size:24px\"><strong>Test 4 &#8211; Test the right IR Sensor<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Finally test the right <strong>IR Sensor<\/strong> by once again positioning the robot a few inches in front of the black tape and pressing button&nbsp;<strong>B4<\/strong>&nbsp;this time. As before, the robot should drive forward until the right <strong>IR Sensor<\/strong> is over the black tape.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>To test the wiring, we are going to use the program WiringTests which can be found in the VSCode folder of the RobotTools2021 that you can find here. If you don&#8217;t yet know how to load and run programs using Visual Studio Code, please review the following chapter of the Minibot tutorial: Running the program.&hellip;&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/testing-the-wiring\/\" class=\"\" rel=\"bookmark\">Read More &raquo;<span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Testing the wiring<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":2,"featured_media":0,"parent":0,"menu_order":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"open","template":"","meta":{"neve_meta_sidebar":"","neve_meta_container":"","neve_meta_enable_content_width":"","neve_meta_content_width":0,"neve_meta_title_alignment":"","neve_meta_author_avatar":"","neve_post_elements_order":"","neve_meta_disable_header":"","neve_meta_disable_footer":"","neve_meta_disable_title":""},"_links":{"self":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/743"}],"collection":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages"}],"about":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/page"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/2"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=743"}],"version-history":[{"count":5,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/743\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":3151,"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/pages\/743\/revisions\/3151"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"http:\/\/gabybot.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=743"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}